      <title>How a Supreme Court Justice is nominated and confirmed by the Senate</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANJustice Anthony Kennedy is stepping down at the end of July, paving way for the president to nominate a new Supreme Court judge, reports CNBC.When a supreme court justice retires, the president has to nominate a qualified candidate.The nominated candidate will then be questioned by the Senate judiciary committee about key issues, a process that takes an average of 60 days.The Senate judiciary committee sends the candidate to the Senate, where they debate  about his or her qualifications.To end the discussion, 60 votes are required in what is known as a cloture motion. According to CBS News, those voting in the Senate tend to reject or accept candidates based on their political leanings.After ending the debate, the Senate will conduct a simple majority vote, requiring at least 51 votes, with the vice president breaking the tie if necessary.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. How US presidents chooses a Supreme Court candidate2. A nominee being questioned by the Senate judiciary committee3. Senate debating whether the candidate is qualified for the job4. Voting process in the SenateVOICEOVER (in English): "When a supreme court justice retires, the president has to nominate a candidate.""The nominated candidate will then be questioned by the Senate judiciary committee about key issues, a process that takes an average of 60 days.""The Senate judiciary committee sends the candidate to the Senate, where they debate back and forth about his or her qualifications. To end the discussion, 60 votes are required in what is known as a cloture motion.""After ending the debate, the Senate will conduct a simple majority vote, requiring at least 51 votes, with the vice president breaking the tie if necessary."SOURCES: The Atlantic, The Washington Post, CBS News, CNBC, Ted-Edhttps://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/06/anthony-kennedy/563939/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/with-anthony-kennedys-departure-the-supreme-court-will-fall-to-chaos/2018/06/27/a052dfde-5a01-11e7-a9f6-7c3296387341_story.html?utm_term=.2208f4a2bbb3https://www.cbsnews.com/news/justice-anthony-kennedy-supreme-court-retiring-scotus-announcement-today-2018-06-27-live-updates/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/27/anthony-kennedy-retiring-from-supreme-court.htmlhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0xnzGSV66x4***]]></description>
