      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA handful of Samsung mobile phones have been sending out camera roll photos via SMS without user permission.As first reported by Gizmodo, Samsung users are complaining of a new bug, which causes phones like the Galaxy S9 and S9+ to send users' stored photos to people on their contacts list without permission.Those who have been affected say evidence of the photo sharing did not appear on the Samsung messages app, but were recorded on phone carrier logs.Many of the complaints have been from T-Mobile subscribers, leading to speculation that the bug was triggered by the carrier's RCS, Rich Communication Services, update which adds features like GIF support, video, location and file sharing to improve texting.While Samsung is still looking into the problem, there are two temporary fixes. Users can revoke Samsung Messages' permissions to access storage, or switch to a different texting app.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of Samsung phones sending photos to contacts2. Depiction of photo sharing leaving a record on carrier log, but not in app3. Depiction of RCS updates triggering glitch4. Depiction of temporary fixes for Samsung glitchVOICEOVER (in English): "A number of Samsung phones, including the Galaxy S9 and S9+, have reportedly been sending users' stored photos to people on their contacts list without permission.""Those who have been affected say evidence of the photo sharing did not appear on the Samsung messages app, but were recorded on phone carrier logs.""Many of the complaints have been from T-Mobile subscribers, leading to speculation that the bug was triggered by the carrier's RCS update, which adds features to improve texting.""While Samsung is still looking into the problem, there are two temporary fixes. Users can revoke Samsung Messages' permissions to access storage, or switch to a different texting app."SOURCES: Gizmodo, Seattle Timeshttps://gizmodo.com/a-bug-in-samsungs-default-texting-app-is-sending-random-1827291759?utm_campaign=socialflow_gizmodo_twitter&utm_medium=socialflow&utm_source=gizmodo_twitterhttps://www.seattletimes.com/business/waposamsung-s-texting-app-apparently-sent-pictures-to-people-s-contacts-without-permission/***]]></description>
