      <title>Third-party app developers may be reading Gmail messages</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANGoogle has confirmed that third-party app developers can sometimes read private emails sent by Gmail users. Third-party developers gain access to emails when Google asks users for permission via a pop-up box that asks to "read, send, delete and manage your email," according to CNet.Google indicates the practice is not a violation of policy. The company says third-party developers need access to help Gmail build various services, reports the BBC.According to the Washington Post, Return Path and Edison Software reviewed private emails.   Return Path allegedly read 8000 user emails from two years ago to help Google develop software.Edison Software reviewed hundreds of emails to build a new software feature, according to the BBC.Edison Software says they have "since stopped this practice."Google said users can revoke access from any third-party apps that users have previously given access to by going to its Security Checkup page, reports EnGadget.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Popup box asking for permission to access Gmail messages2. Return Path reading email to develop software for Gmail.3. Edison Software reading emails to create the 'Smart Reply' function on Gmail4. Showing that Gmail has a Security Checkup page where people can check if their emails have been accessed by third-party apps.VOICEOVER (in English): "Google has confirmed that third-party app developers can sometimes read private emails sent by Gmail users. Developers gain access when Google asks users for permission via a pop-up box the app asks to 'read, send, delete and manage your email.'""Return Path allegedly read 8000 user emails from two years ago to develop Google's software.""Edison Software reviewed hundreds of emails to build a new software feature.""EnGadget reports Google said users can revoke access from any third-party apps by going to its Security Checkup page. "SOURCES: BBC, CNet, EnGadgethttps://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44699263https://www.cnet.com/news/third-party-gmail-apps-reportedly-let-employees-read-peoples-emails/https://www.engadget.com/2018/07/03/third-party-app-developers-reading-gmail/***]]></description>
