      <title>Man fleeing Pompeii eruption killed via asphyxiation, not giant stone: archaeologists</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANNew evidence has been unearthed in the case of the history's unluckiest man.Archaeologists searching the site of the man believed to have been crushed by a stone block during the Mt Vesuvius eruption in 79 A.D. have found the rest of his remains.They found the other remains buried deeper below the man's lower body in a tunnel created several hundred years ago. They recovered his thorax, upper limbs and skull.Analysis of the remains revealed they belonged to a 30 year-old man with a limp, reports CNN. Archaeologists now believe the man's death was brought about by pyroclastic asphyxiation resulting from the eruption.Researchers say more analysis needs to be performed on the bones in order to get a better picture of the man's final moments.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of dig site and new bones2. Depiction of bones inside man3. Depiction of man in ancient Rome area4. Depiction of pyroclastic flow and asphyxiationVOICEOVER (in English): "Archaeologists searching the site of a man believed to have been crushed by a stone block during the Mt Vesuvius eruption in 79 A.D. have found the rest of his remains.""They found the other remains buried deeper below the man's lower body in a tunnel created several hundred years ago.""They recovered his thorax, upper limbs and skull"."Analysis of the remains revealed they belonged to a 30 year-old man with a limp.""Archaeologists now believe the man's death was brought about by pyroclastic asphyxiation resulting from the eruption."SOURCES: Parco Archeologico di Pompei, CNNhttp://www.pompeiisites.org/Sezione.jsp?titolo=Head%20of%20the%20fugitive%20discovered&idSezione=7742https://edition.cnn.com/2018/06/30/europe/pompeii-victim-new-f