      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA new report claims the benefits of legalizing marijuana in New York outweighs the risks.Medical marijuana is allowed but tightly regulated in New York. It can only be taken by patients with certain conditions in pill, oil, or vape form  smoking and direct ingestion are not permitted.The state limits the number of medical marijuana dispensaries and requires vertical integration, which means businesses must grow, harvest, and manufacture what they sell.Many are pushing for full legalization, but Governor Andrew Cuomo isn't fully on board, famously calling marijuana a "gateway drug". However, a new report from the state Department of Health supports legalizing recreational use in New York, finding that it could bring millions in tax revenue.The report predicts that the move could also decrease opioid use and reduce criminal arrests which disproportionately affect minorities.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of medical marijuana regulations in New York2. Depiction of vertical integration in New York dispensaries3. Depiction of potential revenue if recreational marijuana is legalized in New York4. Depiction of other benefits of legalizing recreational marijuanaVOICEOVER (in English): "Marijuana for medical use is allowed but tightly regulated in New York. It can only be taken by patients with certain conditions in pill, oil, or vape form  no smoking or direct ingestion.""The state limits the number of medical marijuana dispensaries and requires vertical integration, which means businesses grow, harvest, and manufacture what they sell.""A new Health Department report supports legalizing recreational marijuana in New York, finding that it could bring millions in tax revenue.