      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANVenezuelans struggling with the country's nonexistent transportation system are resorting to dangerous and often illegal means of getting around.Reuters reports that two years ago, passenger buses in Venezuela numbered at least 280,000, but have disappeared gradually due to expensive or unavailable parts.Public transportation has become scarce, with 95% of buses, cars, and taxis no longer on the road. Instead, residents are relying on over 150,000 unlicensed vehicles, nicknamed "kennels" or "dog carts", to get to their destination.This alternative means of transport often takes takes the form of delivery trucks or vans that standing passengers can cram themselves into.The "kennels" are so named for their cramped and unsafe conditions, which this year alone has caused 39 deaths and 275 injuries, according to opposition lawmaker Nora Bracho.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of Venezuela passenger buses disappearing2. Depiction of scarce public transportation3. Depiction of passengers riding a 'kennel'4. Depiction of dangers of 'kennels'VOICEOVER (in English): "Two years ago, passenger buses in Venezuela numbered at least 280,000, but have disappeared gradually due to expensive or unavailable parts.""Public transportation has become scarce, with 95% of buses, cars, and taxis no longer on the road. Instead, residents are relying on over 150,000 unlicensed 'kennels'.""This alternative means of transport often takes takes the form of delivery trucks or vans that standing passengers can cram themselves into.""The 'kennels' are so named for their cramped and unsafe conditions, which this year alone has caused 39 deaths and 275 injuries."SOURCES: Reuters, Miami Heraldhttps://ww