      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANRealnetworks has announced that it will offer facial recognition technology to schools for free, with the aim at making schools in U.S. safe, Geekwire reported.According to Realnetworks, SAFR is a highly accurate facial recognition software powered by artificial intelligence; it works with IP cameras to match faces in real-time.Schools will need a database with photos of people authorized to be on campus. When an unauthorized person or someone who poses potential threat appears on campus, SAFR notifies a member of the staff.Realnetworks says the facial data and images SAFR collects are encrypted as a privacy protection and the school gets to keep them.SAFR is also designed to function in rural schools with limited internet connectivity.However, facial recognition tech in general  and for kids in school in particular  is a growing area of concern for privacy supporters and parents alike, Geekwire reported.The tech is currently being tested at a school in Seattle where students can unlock a gate by smiling at a surveillance camera.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Introduce SAFR.2. SAFR identifies unauthorized personnel with via the photos it has stored.3. The photos SAFR stored are encrypted and school gets to keep them.4. SAFR can also work in rural schools.VOICEOVER (in English): "According to provider Realnetworks, SAFR is a highly accurate facial recognition software powered by artificial intelligence, it works with IP cameras to match faces in real-time.""Schools will need a database with photos of people authorized to be on campus. When an unauthorized person or someone who poses potential threat appears on campus, SAFR notifies a member of the staff.""Realnetworks said the facial data and images SAFR collects are encrypted as a privacy protection and the school gets to keep them.""SAFR is also designed to function in rural schools with limited internet connectivity."SOURCES: https://www.geekwire.com/2018/realnetworks-debuts-facial-recognition-software-k-12-schools-raising-ethical-questions/https://safr.ai/k12/***]]></description>
