      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA study conducted by Russian scientists in collaboration with Princeton University found 300 prehistoric worms in Yakutia, one of the coldest regions of Russia.Two of the worms were "shown to contain viable nematodes", also known as roundworms, reports the Siberian Times.One worm is estimated to be around 32,000 years old while the other is around 42,000 years old.One of the worms was found in an ancient squirrel burrow's permafrost, while the other was found by the Alazeya River.After being defrosted in a laboratory at The Institute of Physico-Chemical and Biological Problems in Moscow, the worms started to move, eat, and show other signs of life.According to the Siberian Times, both the worms are female and are part of the "oldest living animals on the planet."RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Showing where frozen worms were found in Russia.2. Showing that two of the worms contained nematodes. 3. Showing the areas where the two worms were found.4. Showing the defrosting of the worms and them showing signs of life.VOICEOVER (in English): "A study conducted by Russian scientists in collaboration with Princeton University found 300 prehistoric worms in Yakutia, one of the coldest regions of Russia.""The Siberian Times reports, two of the worms were 'shown to contain viable nematodes' also known as roundworms.""One of the worms was found in an ancient squirrel burrow's permafrost, while the other was found by a river.""After being defrosted in a laboratory in Moscow, the worms started to move, eat, and show other signs of life."SOURCES: Ancient Origins.met, RT, The Siberian Times, Viable Nematodes from Late Pleistocene Permafrost of the Kolyma River Lowland Studyhttps://www.ancien